In C#, there isn't a direct equivalent of Python's `pass` keyword, but you can achieve the same effect by simply placing an empty statement using a semicolon (`;`). This acts as a no-operation (no-op) placeholder where code is syntactically required but you don't want to execute any commands. Here's how you can implement it in C#:

```csharp
int a = 5;
if (a == 5)
{
    // Do nothing
    ;
}
else
{
    Console.WriteLine("Hello World");
}
```

In this example, the semicolon (`;`) inside the `if` block acts as an empty statement, indicating that no action should be taken when the condition is true.
